{
  "texts": [
    "Second, unlike feature importance methods that include all features, counterfactual explanations often focus on a small, selective subset of features.",
    "This selectiveness could introduce bias in the explanations.",
    "For example, explanations with specific features could be chosen to hide the fact a model is based on unethical features (see an elaborated example in Sect. 3).",
    "Our study aims to analyze the disagreement problem in counterfactual explanation algorithms, considering their unique challenges and significant role in ensuring ethical and transparent use of AI.",
    "It's noteworthy that, although the disagreement problem has received attention in the context of feature importance methodologies, a comprehensive quantification of this challenge within counterfactual algorithms remains unaddressed."
  ]
}